PRESIDENT Samia Suluhu Hassan and the US Vice President Kamala Harris on Friday held a historic meeting with Samia urging Washington to encourage more of the private sector from the U.S. to work with Tanzania. "My only request here is to urge the US government to further encourage the private sector to work with us," she told Kamala. "My government would like to see our relationship grow and be strengthened to the highest level." The historic meeting between the two leaders has been a unique one bringing together President Samia, the first woman to lead Tanzania and Kamala the first black woman to hold the post of Vice President. Ahead of their meeting, Kamala told reporters that talks with President Samia would focus on strengthening democracy, investment and economic growth, and health. "Our administration is very committed to strengthening relations with Tanzania and African countries in general," Kamala said. "This has become an area of ​​focus and priority for the president [Joe Biden] and for me." This is the second time that President Samia has paid a visit to the United States. Her first visit included an address to the 76th session of the United Nations General Assembly (UNGA) in September 2021.